    "Statistics for Machine Learning\n",
    "\n",
    " what is statistics :\n",
    "      it is study ok data how to collect, analyze, interpret, and present it.\n",
    "  what is data :\n",
    "      the data it  is a collect of information \n",
    "       it can be\n",
    "       -number\n",
    "       -image\n",
    "       -audio\n",
    "       -text\n",
    "  why we use statictics : In Machine Learning, statistics helps us understand data before applying algorithms. \n",
    "   datas are two types:\n",
    "     -Qualitative Data (Categorical):\n",
    "      it is use to  discribe qualities or characteristics its non numerical data(cannot preform mathematical operation) eg:gender,color,bloodgroup\n",
    "      types of Qualitative Data:\n",
    "        Nominal Data:\n",
    "          Categories without order.\n",
    "          Examples: Gender (male/female), blood type (A/B/O), colors (red/blue/green).\n",
    "          Cannot be ranked or measured numerically.\n",
    "        Ordinal Data:\n",
    "          Categories with a meaningful order but no fixed scale.\n",
    "          Examples: Education level (primary, secondary, graduate), satisfaction ratings (poor, fair, good, excellent).\n",
    "          Ranking is possible, but differences between ranks are not measurable.\n",
    "     -Quantitative Data (Numerical)\n",
    "      it is a data consists of numbers and represent Quantitative(preform mathematical operation) eg:age,height,weight,salary \n",
    "      types of Quantitative Data:\n",
    "        Discrete Data:\n",
    "          Countable values, often integers (whole number).\n",
    "          Examples: Number of students in a class, goals scored in a match, cars in a parking lot.\n",
    "          Cannot take fractional values.\n",
    "        Continuous Data:\n",
    "          Measurable values that can take any value within a range.\n",
    "          Examples: Height, weight, temperature, time.\n",
    "          Can include decimals and fractions\n",
    "      -Extended Classification (Numerical Scales)\n",
    "       Extended classification of numerical data uses scales of measurement to distinguish how numbers behave in analysis.\n",
    "      types of Extended Classification:\n",
    "       Interval Data:\n",
    "          Numbers with equal intervals between values.\n",
    "          No true zero (zero doesn’t mean “none”).\n",
    "          Examples:\n",
    "          Temperature in Celsius or Fahrenheit (0°C ≠ no temperature).\n",
    "          Calendar years (year 0 doesn’t mean “no time”).\n",
    "          You can add and subtract, but ratios are meaningless (20°C is not “twice as hot” as 10°C).\n",
    "        Ratio Data:\n",
    "          Numbers with equal intervals and a true zero (0 = none).\n",
    "          Examples:\n",
    "          Age (0 years = no age).\n",
    "          Weight (0 kg = no weight).\n",
    "          Income (₹0 = no income). \n",
    "          You can add, subtract, multiply, and divide. Ratios are meaningful (20 kg is twice 10 kg).\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "  Type\t    |Nature\t  |Examples\t                        | Fractions Allowed?| True Zero?\n",
    "  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "  Discrete  |\tCount   |numbers\tStudents, goals scored\t|No\t                |   Yes\n",
    "  Continuous|\tMeasured| nums\tHeight, weight, time\t    |Yes\t              |   Yes\n",
    "  Interval\t|Numeric  |scale\tTemperature (°C, °F)\t    |Yes\t              |   No\n",
    "   Ratio\t  |Numeric  |scale\tAge, income, weight\t      |Yes\t              |   Yes\n",
    "\n",
    "Why Statistics is Important in ML?\n",
    "\n",
    "- Helps understand data distribution\n",
    "- Detects patterns and relationships\n",
    "- Improves model performance\n",
    "- Helps in decision making\n",
    "\n",
    "there are two types of statictics \n",
    " -Descriptive Statistics(population):\n",
    "    it is used to discribe, organize raw data into meaningful summaries(no preduction ,no guessing)\n",
    "    it is also called as the population it  is mean all set of data \n",
    "    Main Categories\n",
    " -Measures of Central Tendency:\n",
    "   Show where the data “centers.”\n",
    "   Examples: Mean (average), Median (middle value), Mode (most frequent value).\n",
    " -Measures of Variability (Dispersion):\n",
    "   Show how spread out the data is.\n",
    "   Examples: Range (max–min), Variance, Standard Deviation, Interquartile Range (IQR).\n",
    " -Measures of Frequency Distribution:\n",
    "   Show how often values occur.\n",
    "   Examples: Counts, Percentages, Frequency tables, Histograms.\n",
    "-Inferential Statistics(sample):\n",
    " use sample data to make conclusions about a larger population.\n",
    "  Main Types of Inferential Statistics\n",
    "  -Hypothesis Testing\n",
    "   Tests assumptions about a population (e.g., “Does this new teaching method improve exam scores?”).\n",
    "   Common tests: t-test, chi-square test, ANOVA, z-test.\n",
    "  -Estimation\n",
    "   Uses sample data to estimate population parameters.\n",
    "   Example: Confidence intervals (e.g., “We are 95% confident the average score lies between 70–75”).\n",
    "  -Regression Analysis\n",
    "   Examines relationships between variables.\n",
    "   Example: Predicting exam performance based on study hours.\n",
    "  -Correlation Analysis\n",
    "  Measures strength and direction of relationships between variables (e.g., Pearson’s correlation coefficient).\n"
   ]
